# React (Vite/Create React App) Deployment Guide on Ubuntu EC2

## Project Structure

``` text
/home/ubuntu/Documents/projects/
└── react-dashboard/
    ├── src/
    ├── public/
    ├── package.json
    ├── vite.config.js
    └── dist/ (created after build)
```

## Prerequisites

``` bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install nginx -y
```

Install Node.js (if not already installed):

``` bash
node -v
npm -v
```

## Install Dependencies

``` bash
cd ~/Documents/projects/react-dashboard
npm install
```

## Build the Application

For Vite:

``` bash
npm run build
```

This creates the `dist` directory.

## Configure Nginx

Create a site configuration:

``` bash
sudo nano /etc/nginx/sites-available/react-dashboard
```

Example configuration:

``` nginx
server {
    listen 3000;
    server_name 13.51.197.121;

    root /home/ubuntu/Documents/projects/react-dashboard/dist;
    index index.html;

    location / {
        try_files $uri $uri/ /index.html;
    }

    location ~* \.(js|css|png|jpg|jpeg|gif|svg|ico|woff|woff2|ttf)$ {
        expires 30d;
        access_log off;
    }
}
```

Enable the site:

``` bash
sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/react-dashboard /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/
```

Test configuration:

``` bash
sudo nginx -t
```

Restart Nginx:

``` bash
sudo systemctl restart nginx
```

## Open Firewall

``` bash
sudo ufw allow 3000/tcp
```

Also add an EC2 Security Group inbound rule:

-   Type: Custom TCP
-   Port: 3000
-   Source: 0.0.0.0/0

## Access the Application

    http://13.51.197.121:3000

## Updating the Application

Whenever you make changes:

``` bash
cd ~/Documents/projects/react-dashboard
npm install        # only if dependencies changed
npm run build
sudo systemctl reload nginx
```

## Troubleshooting

Check Nginx status:

``` bash
sudo systemctl status nginx
```

View logs:

``` bash
sudo tail -f /var/log/nginx/error.log
sudo tail -f /var/log/nginx/access.log
```

Check listening ports:

``` bash
sudo ss -tulpn | grep 3000
```

Validate configuration:

``` bash
sudo nginx -t
```

## Production Recommendation

Once you have a domain:

-   Serve React over ports **80** and **443**
-   Use Let's Encrypt for HTTPS
-   Avoid exposing development ports publicly
-   Keep React as static files served by Nginx
